data.content:
Here are the recommended replacements:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0);                    // ✅ keep, or use:
    // CollectionAssert.That.IsNotEmpty(users);         //    (MSTest v3.7+)

    CollectionAssert.AllSatisfy(users,                  // ✅ replaces .All() + Assert.IsTrue
        u => Assert.IsTrue(u.IsActive));

    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);                    // ✅ replaces Count == 3 check

    Assert.IsNotNull(users.Single(u =>                  // ✅ replaces != null check
        u.Role == "Admin"));
}
```

**Key MSTest collection assertions:**

| Instead of | Use |
|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(list.Count > 0)` | `CollectionAssert.That.IsNotEmpty(list)` (v3.7+) |
| `Assert.IsTrue(list.All(…))` | `CollectionAssert.AllSatisfy(list, …)` |
| `Assert.IsTrue(a.SequenceEqual(b))` | `CollectionAssert.AreEqual(expected, actual)` |
| `Assert.IsTrue(list.Contains(x))` | `CollectionAssert.Contains(list, x)` |
| `Assert.IsTrue(list.Count == n)` | `Assert.AreEqual(n, list.Count)` |

The main benefit: **better failure messages**. `Assert.IsTrue(false)` just says "expected true", while `CollectionAssert` tells you *which element* or *what collection* failed.
